<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n12128i"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12128i">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12128i"> 128(i)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Froissart &amp; Renart</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">C&apos;&eacute;tait l&apos;effondrement de l&apos;empire grec, l&apos;&eacute;crasement du tsar Lazare et de ses Serbes &agrave; Kossovo, le grand deuil de l&apos;Occident dont la fleur de la chevalerie, partie pour la croisade contre l&apos;Islam, p&eacute;rissait ou &eacute;tait faite prisonni&egrave;re dans le d&eacute;sastre de Nicopolis. Ajoutez &agrave; cela l&apos;anarchie des id&eacute;es. Ajoutez surtout le cynisme des m&oelig;urs. C&apos;est le si&egrave;cle qui a enfant&eacute; le cauteleux roman de <cite>Renart</cite> et aussi Froissard, le pr&ecirc;tre sans id&eacute;al qui raconte ses aventures d&apos;amour. <br><font color="green">[This was the period of the downfall of the Greek Empire, the crushing of Czar Lazar and his Serbs in Kosovo, the great disaster of the West when the flower of chivalry, having departed in a crusade against Islam, had died or had been taken prisoner at Nicopolis. Add to this the anarchy of ideas. And moral cynism. This was the century of the naughty novel <cite><mark>Renart</mark></cite> and of <mark>Froissard</mark>, the priest without ideals who tells of his amorous adventures.]</font> <small> Matthieu-Maxime Gorce, <a name="STVF" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#STVF"><cite title="source">Saint Vincent Ferrier</cite></a> (1924) 63</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Jean Froissart (c 1330-c 1410): historian, wrote <cite>Chroniques</cite>, an account of the Hundred Years War. He was also a distinguished poet. Renart is Reynard the Fox, as he appears in the <i>Roman de Renart</i>. </mm> </dd></dl>
